                <section id="cec562e95eb5411ab4a9131560b912b4">
                        <title>Simple Variable Code</title>
                        <body>
                                <p id="fedcbbc2d2734a1f9321e8f6957e8d83">In this section, we add the idea of a <em style="italic">variable</em> in code. A variable is like a box that holds one value the code puts there. Here is a line of code that stores the value 7 in a variable, <em style="italic">x</em>: 
                                </p>
                                <codeblock id="f06a6af1956647908b64104bc8d92fdc" syntax="java" highlight="" number="false" start="">
x = 7;
                                </codeblock>
                                <p id="efc7a5bcaa6f4f82bb88a3dcc1d25fda">The variable <em style="italic">x</em> is like a box, holding whatever value is stored in it. Later uses of <em style="italic">x</em> in the code retrieve the value from the variable. Storing a value in a variable in JavaScript requires using the equal sign (=).</p>
                                <p id="a54c989aa60144da8a8c442fe84841b7" />
                                <image id="cb42fe698a16491fa77381a7cb9dc82a" src="../webcontent/code-variable.png" alt="variable x as a box holding the value 7" style="inline" vertical-align="middle">
                                        <caption>
                                                <p id="a2fca45c38c247a89ce94ec3ecdb9c58" />
                                        </caption>
                                        <popout enable="false"></popout>
                                </image>
                        </body>
                </section>
                <section id="eb55bffc8aa541439c3f715d067de41a">
                        <title>Example: Variables in Principles of Computing</title>
                        <body>
                                <p id="fdffab8b1e064df8a27bc338391e91b3">For Principles of Computing, we use variables in a simple way. One line, like the example above, will store a value into a variable. Later lines can use the variable to retrieve the stored value. Run this example to see what it does.</p>
                                <codeblock id="d6bd7362a4884c05ba3711e2b64bee88" syntax="text" highlight="" number="false" start=""></codeblock>
                                <wb:inline idref="d9bd71f02ca144bf9246d0631cb2d086" purpose="learnbydoing" />
                                <p id="c16296db96c748ca8e43757b564be4f8">
                                        <em>Try it yourself:</em> Change the 7 to 14, and then run it to see the changed output.</p>
                                <p id="cbf3472b2e3a4526a5e23859c4bcfa96">Variables used in this way work as a shorthand. The code uses = to store a value into a variable, and then uses that variable on later lines to retrieve that value. In the simplest case, this just works to avoid the work of repeatedly typing in a value. All computer languages have some form of variable used for storing and retrieving values.</p>
                        </body>
